04627nam a22007215i 9781442682412DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20161997onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1002247608  a(OCoLC)1004873045  a(OCoLC)1011454472  a(OCoLC)1013952321  a(OCoLC)999369783  a97814426824127 a10.3138/97814426824122doi  a(DE-B1597)465040  a(OCoLC)944177320  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aJC233.N52bM24 1997eb 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a320/.011 aMcIntyre, Alex, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Sovereignty of Joy :bNietzsche's Vision of Grand Politics /cAlex McIntyre. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aToronto Studies in Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgmentss -- tAbbreviations -- t1. Joy, Sovereignty, and Atopia -- t2. Joy in the Actual -- t3. The Seasons of a People: Community and Individuality in the Cycle of Natural Morality -- t4. Hierarchy and the Overman -- t5. Nietzsche Contra Rousseau -- t6. Communion in Joy: Will to Power and Eternal Return in Grand Politics -- t7. The Poetry of the Future -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNietzsche's philosophical effort is fundamentally a response to the political question of who should rule and upon what basis in the era following the death of God. Because Nietzsche's response to nihilism is so unique, scholars still debate the nature and success of his political philosophy in overcoming a spirit of revenge. In The Sovereignty of Joy: Nietzsche's Vision of Grand Politics, Alex McIntyre suggests that a sense of tragic joy is the legislating experience at the heart of Nietzsche's philosophy. A Dionysian exuberance animates all of Nietzsche's central ideas -- will to power, self-mastery, the Overman, amor fati, eternal return -- and especially his 'grand politics,' which McIntyre argues is the political elaboration of the sovereignty of joy.This study interprets Nietzsche's conception of tragic joy as the affirmation of the fullness of becoming at every moment, an affirmation which overcomes revenge and nihilism by embracing suffering and loss. As the embodiment of tragic joy, the Overman represents a new form of philosophical statesmanship that cannot be reduced to either a politics of domination or an idealistic utopianism, for such an interpretation ignores the 'atopian' nature of Nietzsche's grand politics. McIntyre characterizes 'atopia' as the double position of the Nietzschean philosopher at both the centre and the periphery of a political culture through the revaluation of all values.By rediscovering the ethos of communion and the creative conception of joy that inform Nietzsche's writings, The Sovereignty of Joy persuasively challenges the notion that Nietzsche's grand politics are power politics or utopian idealism in another form.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aJoy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268241240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442682412423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442682412.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK